# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: don-kessinger
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:don-kessinger/1951-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1951 throughout the world.
[src:don-kessinger/1951-in-baseball-p01] Baseball's Shot Heard 'Round the World gives the New York Giants the National League Pennant in the third game of a best-of-three-games tiebreaker series over the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:don-kessinger/1951-in-baseball-p01] Although the Negro American League would last until 1960, 1951 was, notably, the last season in which the Negro American League was considered major-league caliber, which was itself the last major Negro league baseball organization.
[src:don-kessinger/1951-in-baseball-p01] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] The **1964 Chicago Cubs season** was the 93rd season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 89th in the National League and the 49th at Wrigley Field.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished eighth in the National League with a record of 76–86, 17 games behind the NL and World Series champion St.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] On February 13, Ken Hubbs, who had been the Cubs starting second baseman in 1963, was killed in a plane crash.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] He was replaced by Joey Amalfitano, who was acquired from the San Francisco Giants a few weeks later.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] On June 15, the Cubs made one of the most infamous deals in baseball history, remembered today simply as "Brock for Broglio".
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] There were six players involved in all, but the most prominent players involved were pitcher Ernie Broglio, who came to the Cubs from the St.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] Louis Cardinals, and outfielder Lou Brock, who went to the Cardinals from the Cubs.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] While Broglio was a serviceable starter for the rest of 1964, he would post ERAs over 6 in each of the next two seasons, and was out of baseball altogether by the end of 1967.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] Brock went on to star for the Cardinals for the next fifteen years, and eventually be elected to the Hall of Fame.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] It is to this day often held up as an example of a lopsided trade outcome.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs in 1963 had been a team that had arrived, finishing over .500 for the first time since 1946.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] They had a great nucleus with Hubbs, Ron Santo, Billy Williams, Ernie Banks, pitchers Dick Ellsworth and Larry Jackson, and Brock.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] In 1963, the Cubs finished second in the league in ERA and second in giving up the fewest runs, earned runs, and walks.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] With Hubbs on the team in 1964, it is highly unlikely the Cubs would have pushed the panic button and traded Brock.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] With Brock batting first, Hubbs second, followed by Williams, Santo, and Banks in 1964, the Cubs would have fielded a strong lineup, as they had in 1963.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] That 1964 lineup featured three future Hall of Famers even without Hubbs and Brock.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] Left fielder Williams batted .312 that year with 33 homers and 98 RBI, and garnered some MVP votes.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] Third baseman Santo batted cleanup, with a .313 average, a major league leading 13 triples, a National League high 86 walks, and a league leading .398 on-base percentage.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] First baseman Banks was fifth in the lineup.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] He batted only .264 that year, but had 23 homers and 95 RBI.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-chicago-cubs-season] With the cloud of Hubbs' untimely passing hanging over their heads, however, the Cubs finished ten games under .500.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1964 throughout the world.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The **1964 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1964.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 4, with the St.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 61st World Series on October 7 and ended with Game 7 on October 15.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] In the fifth iteration of this World Series matchup, the Cardinals defeated the Yankees, four games to three, capturing their seventh championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1946.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] As of 2024, the Cardinals are the only National League team to have an edge over the Yankees in series played (3–2), despite holding a losing record in World Series games against them (13–15).
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Los Angeles Dodgers from the 1963 season.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The 35th All-Star Game was held on July 7 at Shea Stadium in New York, New York, home of the New York Mets.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] This season is often remembered for the end of the New York Yankees' third dynasty, as they won their 29th American League Championship in 44 seasons.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The 1964 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 10 teams.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other nine teams of their respective league.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American League since the 1961 season and by the National League since the 1962 season, and would be used until 1969.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 13, featuring four teams.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 4, which saw 18 teams play.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 7 and October 15.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (4 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Indians and New York Yankees had two tie games each.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles, Detroit Tigers, Kansas City Athletics, and Minnesota Twins had one each.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The Los Angeles Dodgers had two tie games.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds and New York Mets had one each.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 7 and ended on October 15 with the St.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the New York Yankees in the 1964 World Series in seven games.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Mets leave the Polo Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and open Shea Stadium (with the AFL's New York Jets) where they would go on to play 45 seasons through 2008.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The Houston Colt .45s would play their final game at Colt Stadium on September 27 against the Los Angeles Dodgers, moving into the Houston Astrodome (as the Houston Astros) for the start of the 1965 season.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC aired weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] By 1964, CBS paid $895,000 total for the rights to six teams, with the New York Yankees getting a $550,000 share.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The six clubs that exclusively played nationally televised games on NBC were paid $1.2 million total.
[src:don-kessinger/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series aired on NBC.
[src:don-kessinger/1965-chicago-cubs-season] The **1965 Chicago Cubs season** was the 94th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 90th in the National League and the 50th at Wrigley Field.
[src:don-kessinger/1965-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished eighth in the National League with a record of 72–90.
[src:don-kessinger/1965-chicago-cubs-season] The 1965 Cubs tied a major league record by turning three triple plays.
[src:don-kessinger/1965-chicago-cubs-season] Bill Faul was on the mound on each occasion.
[src:don-kessinger/1966-chicago-cubs-season] The **1966 Chicago Cubs season** was the 95th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 91st in the National League and the 51st at Wrigley Field.
[src:don-kessinger/1966-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished tenth and last in the National League with a record of 59–103, 36 games behind the NL Champion Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:don-kessinger/1966-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs would not lose 100 or more games in a season for another 46 seasons.
[src:don-kessinger/1966-chicago-cubs-season] One of the defining trades in Cubs history occurred on April 21, when the Cubs acquired future Cy Young Award winner Ferguson Jenkins in a trade with the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1968 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 39th playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 9, 1968, at the Astrodome in Houston, Texas the home of the Houston Astros of the National League, making this the first All-Star Game to be played indoors.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the National League defeating the American League 1–0.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It is the only All-Star Game played without a run batted in (RBI).
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first night All-Star Game since 1944.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Apart from the 1969 game (which was originally scheduled to be played at night but was postponed to the following afternoon due to rain), all subsequent All-Star Games have been played at night.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The next indoor All-Star Game was eleven years later, at the Kingdome in Seattle.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League was limited to three hits, unable to get a rally going against Don Drysdale, Juan Marichal, Steve Carlton and Tom Seaver, all future Hall of Famers.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] A first-inning run scored by Willie Mays on a single, an errant pickoff attempt, a wild pitch by Luis Tiant and a double-play ball gave the winning National league the only run they would need.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Don Wert's eighth-inning double momentarily gave the AL a threat to tie the game, but Seaver struck out the side.
[src:don-kessinger/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the ninth, with two out, Jerry Koosman was brought in from the bullpen to face Carl Yastrzemski, whose strikeout ended the game.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, Kessinger was considered one of the best shortstops in baseball.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] For nine consecutive seasons he formed a productive middle-infield partnership with second baseman Glenn Beckert.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He is also notable for being the last player-manager in American League history.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] A four sport All-State and All-America athlete for the Forrest City High School Mustangs, Kessinger graduated high school in 1960 and went on to the University of Mississippi.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] During his collegiate years, he earned All-Conference, All-SEC, and All-America honors in both basketball and baseball for the Rebels, and was initiated into the Sigma Nu fraternity.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger also played for the Peoria Pacers, of the Central Illinois Collegiate League (a summer league for collegiate players) in its founding year, 1963.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He was signed by the Chicago Cubs as an amateur free agent on June 19, 1964.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger was assigned to play for the Double-A Fort Worth Cats before making his major league debut on September 7, 1964.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He returned to the minor leagues with the Dallas-Fort Worth Spurs for the 1965 season, but was brought back by the Cubs in June of that year and became their starting shortstop.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] The 1965 season would mark the first of nine consecutive seasons in which Kessinger would work alongside Cubs' second baseman Glenn Beckert.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He ended the season hitting for a .201 batting average and led the National League shortstops in errors but, showed some promise by leading the league in range factor.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] As the 1966 season got underway, Kessinger continued to struggle with his hitting when, new Cubs manager Leo Durocher encouraged him to become a switch hitter.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] With the help of coach Pete Reiser, his hitting began to improve, in posting a .304 batting average during the second half of the season.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Durocher made Kessinger his lead off hitter, a spot he would hold for many years.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He ended the year with a career-high .274 batting average and led the league's shortstops with 474 assists.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger continued to improve his fielding and in 1968, he was recognized as one of the top shortstops in the league when he was voted to be the starting shortstop for the National League in the 1968 All-Star Game.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] At the end of the season, he ranked first among the league's shortstops in range factor and, led the entire league in assists.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] While he also led the league in errors, he attributed this to the fact that he reached more ground balls than the average shortstop.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger repeated as an All-Star in 1969, in a year which saw the entire Chicago Cubs infield join him on the 1969 All-Star team, with Kessinger and Cubs' third baseman Ron Santo in the starting line-up.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] In 1969, he set a major league single-season record for shortstops by playing in 54 games without committing an error, breaking the record previously set by Chico Carrasquel in 1951.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] The Cubs were in first place in the National League Eastern Division for 180 days of the 1969 season, before going 8–17 in their final 25 games, while the New York "Miracle" Mets went 37–11 in their final 48 games to clinch the Eastern Division pennant.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Despite the Cubs' late-season collapse, Kessinger scored 109 runs, hit for a .273 batting average with a career-high 181 hits, including 38 doubles; second-most in the league.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He led the league's shortstops in putouts, finished second in fielding percentage and once again led the entire National League in assists.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He finished in 15th place in balloting for the 1969 National League Most Valuable Player Award and won his first Gold Glove Award.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] In his book, *The Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*, baseball historian Bill James cited manager Durocher's method of using his regular players everyday without any rest days as a factor in the Cubs' collapse.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] On September 9, 1969, Kessinger was in the batters box at Shea Stadium when a black cat emerged from under the stands.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] After staring at Kessinger and Santo (in the on-deck circle), it headed toward the Cubs' bench, where Durocher received a raised tail and hiss.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] During a July 4 interview in 1969 with then St.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Louis Cardinals sportscaster Harry Caray, Cubs pitcher, Ferguson Jenkins, gave a name to Kessinger's trademark play at shortstop—"The Down Pat".
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Children from throughout WGN-TV's viewing audience widely copied it on playgrounds and in Little League games, and his fellow players typically stood in awe.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Carey noted that Kessinger would regularly go to his right, toward left field, spear the ground ball and then, demonstrating a unique agility, reverse while in the air as he whipped the ball toward first base.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] "Do you think it might be because Don was a great basketball player?" asked Caray.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Without hesitation, Jenkins responded, "In the past five games he's made many great plays to his right.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger had another successful season in 1970, producing a .266 batting average while scoring 100 runs.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He led the entire league in assists for the third consecutive year and claimed his second Gold Glove Award.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] On June 17, 1971, he went 6-for-6, becoming the first Cubs with a six hit game in nearly 34 years.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He continued to be one of the cornerstones of the Cubs' infield, earning three more All-Star berths in 1971, 1972 and 1974.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] In October 1975, after 11 seasons with the Cubs, Kessinger was traded to the St.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Louis Cardinals—for pitcher Mike Garman and infielder Bobby Hrapmann.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He was the last remaining Cub from the 1969 season when they almost won the pennant.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] The 33-year-old Kessinger still played well in St.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Louis, ending the season with a .320 on-base percentage and was second in the league in range factor.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] In August 1977, he was traded to the Chicago White Sox—for pitcher Steve Staniland—who were seeking to bolster their infield strength.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] The White Sox held a "Don Kessinger Night" on September 8, 1978, where 31,000 Chicago baseball fans (said to consist, in Baseball Digest, of nearly equal numbers of Sox and Cubs fans) thanked #11 for his years of service at shortstop.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] On October 19, 1978, White Sox President Bill Veeck named Kessinger to be the team's player-manager (the last in AL history).
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He was managing at Comiskey Park on July 12, 1979, when the infamous "Disco Demolition Night" took place, and wisely locked his players in the locker room between games, avoiding the near-riot.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] With the White Sox languishing in 5th place in the standings, Kessinger resigned on August 2, 1979 and was replaced by Tony La Russa.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] In a 16-year major league career, Kessinger played in 2,078 games, accumulating 1,931 hits in 7,651 at bats for a .252 career batting average along with 14 home runs, 527 runs batted in and an on-base percentage of .314.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger however struggled as a pinch-hitter in his MLB career, going 0-for-37 with just one RBI.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He retired with a .965 fielding percentage.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] A six-time All-Star, Kessinger won the National League Gold Glove for shortstops in 1969 and 1970.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] In three different seasons with the Cubs, he turned 100 or more double plays.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger had 6,212 assists during his career, ranking him 14th all-time among major league shortstops.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger received 0.5% of the vote on the Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 1985, his only appearance on the balloting.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger married Carolyn Crawley—also from Forrest City—in 1965.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] One son, Keith, was drafted by the Baltimore Orioles in 1989 and had a brief career (nine years, minors and majors, in the Reds and Cubs organizations) as a professional baseball player.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Another son, Kevin, was drafted by the Chicago Cubs in 1992.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Prior to the 1991 season, Kessinger was hired as the head baseball coach at his alma mater, the University of Mississippi.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger would spend six years as the Ole Miss skipper, leading the Rebels to four 30-win seasons.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] His 1995 team produced a school record for wins, going 40–22 and earning the school's first NCAA Regional bid since 1977.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Ole Miss finished on the verge of its first College World Series appearance since 1972, placing second at the NCAA Atlantic I Regional behind host Florida State.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Both of his sons had the opportunity to play for their father at Ole Miss.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Following the 1996 season, Kessinger resigned his head coaching position to become Mississippi's associate athletics director for internal affairs, while concurrently serving as chair of the NCAA Baseball Rules Committee.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He finished with a six-year record of 185–153.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger was an honoree at the 1976 Chicago Baseball Writers Diamond Dinner, where he was presented with the Ken Hubbs Award, given for exemplary conduct both on and off the field.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He has also honored by the Chicagoland Sports Hall of Fame, Chicago Cubs Hall of Fame, Wrigley Field Walk of Fame, Ole Miss Sports Hall of Fame, Mississippi Sports Hall of Fame, National High School Hall of Fame and the Arkansas Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] He was also recognized as the 12th Best Athlete in the history of the Southeastern Conference in 2007 and named to the Ole Miss All-Century Basketball Team in 2008.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Presently, he is the President of Kessinger Enterprises, Inc. and owns a real estate business in Oxford, Mississippi.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] While writing his 2012 novel *Calico Joe*—detailing a fictional young player on the Cubs in the early 1970s—author John Grisham drew from Kessinger's memories.
[src:don-kessinger/don-kessinger] Kessinger's grandson, Grae, also became a professional baseball player who made his major league debut for the Houston Astros in 2023.
